<exploration xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="PA-8a-5x" component="static">
  <introduction>
    <p>
        Consider the alternating geometric series 
        <me>
            S = \sum_{k=0}^{\infty} (-1)^k \left( \frac{4}{5} \right)^k = 1 - \frac{4}{5} + \frac{16}{25} - \cdots + (-1)^{n-1} \left( \frac{4}{5} \right)^{n-1} + \cdots
        </me>.  
        We want to explore how the partial sums of the series compare to and approximate the exact sum of the series.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <task workspace="1cm" xml:id="PA-8a-5x-task-0">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Recall that the <m>n</m>th partial sum, <m>S_n</m>, is the sum of the first <m>n</m> terms of the infinite geometric series <m>S</m>.  This means that
                <me>
                    S_n = \sum_{k=0}^{n-1} (-1)^k \left( \frac{4}{5} \right)^k = 1 - \frac{4}{5} + \frac{16}{25} - \cdots + (-1)^{n-1} \left( \frac{4}{5} \right)^{n-1}
                </me>. 
            Note that the exact fractional values of <m>S_3</m>, <m>S_4</m>, <m>\ldots</m>, <m>S_8</m>, have been recorded below along with their decimal representations.       
        </p>
        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow>n \amp= 1 \amp S_1 \amp= 1 \amp </mrow>
                <mrow>n \amp= 2 \amp S_2 \amp= \frac{1}{5} = 0.2 \amp S_1 - S_2 = <fillin characters="4" /> </mrow>
                <mrow>n \amp= 3 \amp S_3 \amp= \frac{21}{25} = 0.84 \amp S_2 - S_3 = <fillin characters="4" /> </mrow>
                <mrow>n \amp= 4 \amp S_4 \amp= \frac{41}{125} = 0.328 \amp S_3 - S_4 = <fillin characters="4" />  </mrow>
                <mrow>n \amp= 5 \amp S_5 \amp= \frac{461}{625} = 0.7376 \amp S_4 - S_5 = <fillin characters="4" />  </mrow>
                <mrow>n \amp= 6 \amp S_6 \amp= \frac{1281}{3125} = 0.40992 \amp S_5 - S_6 = <fillin characters="4" />  </mrow>
                <mrow>n \amp= 7 \amp S_7 \amp= \frac{10501}{15625} = 0.672064 \amp S_6 - S_7 = <fillin characters="4" />  </mrow>
                <mrow>n \amp= 8 \amp S_8 \amp= \frac{36121}{78125} = 0.4623488 \amp S_7 - S_8 = <fillin characters="4" />  </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>           
        <p>
            By computing the differences between consecutive partial sums, fill in the blank spaces provided above.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
  <task workspace="2cm" xml:id="PA-8a-5x-task-1">
    <statement>
        <p>
            What do you notice about the differences between consecutive partial sums as the value of <m>n</m> increases?  There are at least two important things you can say.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
  <task workspace="2cm" xml:id="PA-8a-5x-task-2">
    <statement>
        <p>
            For the given infinite geometric series 
            <me>
                S = \sum_{k=0}^{\infty} (-1)^k \left( \frac{4}{5} \right)^k 
            </me>
            identify the values of <m>a</m> and <m>r</m> and use <xref ref="eq-8a-3-infinite-geometric-sum">Equation</xref> to find the exact value of <m>S</m>.  State the sum of the infinite geometric series both as a fraction and as its decimal representation.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
  <task workspace="1cm" xml:id="PA-8a-5x-task-3">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Consider the same information from (a) regarding the partial sums of the geometric series:
            <md>
                <mrow>n \amp= 1 \amp S_1 \amp= 1 \amp S_1 - S = <fillin characters="4" /> </mrow>
                <mrow>n \amp= 2 \amp S_2 \amp= \frac{1}{5} = 0.2 \amp S_2 - S = <fillin characters="4" /> </mrow>
                <mrow>n \amp= 3 \amp S_3 \amp= \frac{21}{25} = 0.84 \amp S_3 - S = <fillin characters="4" /> </mrow>
                <mrow>n \amp= 4 \amp S_4 \amp= \frac{41}{125} = 0.328 \amp S_4 - S = <fillin characters="4" />  </mrow>
                <mrow>n \amp= 5 \amp S_5 \amp= \frac{461}{625} = 0.7376 \amp S_5 - S = <fillin characters="4" />  </mrow>
                <mrow>n \amp= 6 \amp S_6 \amp= \frac{1281}{3125} = 0.40992 \amp S_6 - S = <fillin characters="4" />  </mrow>
                <mrow>n \amp= 7 \amp S_7 \amp= \frac{10501}{15625} = 0.672064 \amp S_7 - S = <fillin characters="4" />  </mrow>
                <mrow>n \amp= 8 \amp S_8 \amp= \frac{36121}{78125} = 0.4623488 \amp S_8 - S = <fillin characters="4" />  </mrow>
            </md>
        </p> 
        <p>
            Use the sum, <m>S</m>, of the geometric series that you found in (c) to compute the difference between each of the first <m>8</m> partial sums, and fill in the corresponding blanks above.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </task>  
  <task workspace="2cm" xml:id="PA-8a-5x-task-4">
    <statement>
        <p>
            What do you notice about the differences between the partial sums and the exact sum of the series as the value of <m>n</m> increases?  There are at least two important things you can say.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
</exploration>

